On 06 Aug 2000 12:09:02 +0300, Mikhael Goikhman wrote:
> 
> On 30 Jun 2000 13:19:11 +0200, Adam Tla/lka wrote:
> > 
> > to obtain focus to any new created window and get focus to last active one    
> > while current active is deleted. First works ok for me but second does not.   
> > I observe that before event is activated the window under the pointer         
> > position is focused (it's not the last active one in this case)               
> > so list order is changed and then event function is useless.                  
> > I am using SloppyFocus.                                                       
> > Strange because it worked properly in 2.2.4 version.                          
> 
> Your observation is correct. LastActive is called after a window under
> the pointer gets a focus, which makes destroy_window event useless in your
> case. This is clearly seen if you uncomment the WindowList line.
> 
> I can see that, like in 2.2.4, M_DESTROY_WINDOW is broadcasted, i.e. added
> to a queue, *before* the focus games on a window under a pointer.
> 
> Ok, I have fixed this problem by making SetSyncMask on all messages in
> FvwmEvent.

This fix (SetSyncMask on all messages) was actually not a relable one.

> For some reason SetSyncMask(fd, M_DESTROY_WINDOW), i.e. 1<<7, has no
> effect for me, but SetSyncMask(fd, 1<<31) does the fix! I am confused.

On some level, 0x80000000 is converted to 0x7fffffff, which is buggy
regardless of signed/unsigned arithmetics. But this is not directly
related to the mentioned problem.

The problem is in this line of PositiveWrite in module_interface.c:

  if ((SyncMask[module] & ptr[1]) && !myxgrabcount)

So, even if a message is set to be synchronized, still it's not guaranteed
that this will be the case. For example, M_DESTROY_WINDOW is always sent
inside of MyXGrab/MyXUnGrab. I removed the myxgrabcount condition bit,
this together with synching on destroy_window fixes the original problem.
I understand this may cause problems, but I see no other solution. I have
tested several cases, like 2 FvwmAnimate, 2 FvwmEvent and see no problems.
I will restore the original condition if there are ones.

> Related issue. FvwmEvent does not SetMessageMask, so it always gets all
> events, which is by itself is not optimal; making all of them synchronized
> can be a little slow. Any thoughts?

Regards,
Mikhael.
